		   <table class="mform"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform" valign="top" id="forumSubject">Etiquette<br clear="all" /><script type="text/javascript">document.title = document.title + ": Thread: Etiquette";</script>
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Sun, Feb 13th 3:46 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=110832765395582215&post=1"><a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=110832765395582215&num=73&page=1&post=1&replyto=110832765395582215"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=110832765395582215></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=503143"><span id=>BuyingWoW</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br />6 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=BuyingWoW&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>I've been playing EQ for 5 years, and lately I have winessed a great increase in players who seem to be missing general consideration for others.&nbsp;&nbsp;More often I am seeing players completely booted from my groups for exhibiting these characteristics.  I thought I'd compile a few of these behaviors in this post.  Maybe it can help educate a few people into becoming a player more groups will want to invite.  I am probably dreaming.. but.. here goes a list of what I call General EQ Etiquette:<br><br>(1) In a group of 6, try to loot only 1 in 6 mobs.  Leave some drops for awhile so that clerics and other classes away from the fight can loot.  Remind groupmates to loot.. some classes are very busy, and they might be your best players.  Checking loot is good; no one wants to see a rare item rot or get ninja'd.  If you feel you must &quot;check&quot; corpses, at least begin by having the share money option on your character turned on.  Also, maybe announce what is on the corpse, since it would seem you have more time than others in the group to do these things.  Further, if you won a big item in a roll, why not relax on the general looting a bit.<br><br>(2) NBG.  The need before greed debate could go on forever.  I personally disagree with NBG and will disband from most groups trying to utilize it.  I find it rewards certain players disproportionately. If a person is present at the camp and is contributing, then he or she deserves a chance at loot.  No one or 2 people deserve loot more.  NBG also promotes lower players congregating, since higher level players with more experience at the camp probably already have the items that drop.  Players with good gear have an important role to play in a group.  They deserve their share of reward.  Likewise, if someone is new to a camp, they should earn their gear just like everyone else who took the time to roll and win.<br><br>(3) Beware of players above 65 who want to Master Loot in zones outside of LDoN; particularly in OoW.  These people often keep valuable items for themselves.  Many items that may seem worthless, such as Bazu Blood, may have a high selling price in the bazaar.  Don't be conned out of your fair share.<br><br>(4) Contributing little to the group DOES get detected, especially by players who have played for a few years.  You may have seen players who appear to be afk for many minutes at a time, or who wander off.  Some simply do not put much effort into their contribution.  In some cases people experience real life distractions that I understand.  However, sometimes these are people playing 2 or more characters in the same or different camps.  Bottom line is, if one or both characters are not contributing much, it is plain selfish and greedy.  I am pleased to see more groups voting to remove many of these sorts of players from their group.  Some players are upfront and honest about boxing.  Others are deceptive.  Some want to gain an extra roll on items and gain extra benefits at the expense of others in the group. My suggestion is, if you witness this in your group, speak up! <br><br>(5) The amount of time a player has been in EQ is far too often overlooked.  I have heard many people boast that they have power-leveled their current character, and have only played a few days &lt;fizzle&gt;.  To them I am cautious.  I far prefer a player with more experience in the game. Even though I usually try my best in EQ, it is unlikely that one of my twinks, with, say, 2 months playing time, can ever measure up to the skills a player would have if they have been playing their class for a lot longer.  There are always exceptions of course, such as E-Bayed accounts.  My point is, if you are looking for a good contributer to your group, don't forget how valuable played experience can be.<br><br>(6) Attitude.  Thankfully, I am starting to see people with terrible attitudes being ignored when LFG.  It demonstrates that people are beginning to tolerating rudeness a lot less.  If you do not want to become of these people, my suggestion is to think before typing. Try not to blame someone for a wipe (maybe try to coach if the player is VERY unskilled).  Another idea is try not to whine about not winning a roll, needing a spell, or having lousy gear.  Many people are starting to see this as childish behavior.<br><br>(7) Monopolizing.  Believe it or not, there are people who use 4 or more computers at the same time and monopolize a single camp.  Meanwhile, others sit around groupless.  I really don't even need to say the words selfish and greedy here.  <br><br>(8) Promote fun.  These are not meant to be ways to make the game mechanical.  Instead it is just a way to save you from being &quot;the weakest link&quot;.  There is still plenty of room to enjoy the game while being good at it.  <br><br>I just compiled this list off of the top of my head right now.  I am sure I have missed stuff that I will think of later.  I'd be very interested in seeing what others people wish to see MORE of, or LESS of, from other players.  <br></p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >73 Replies</td></tr></table>
</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td>

