		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9795 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.03]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Oh. And just to add to the general topic.<br><br>Most groups use a CAWU system rather then NBG (although I suppose they are similar). If you can use an item that drops, and can show that you *will* use it, you get the drop. It's just not that hard. Some piece of gear drops. Someone who CAWU, will link their current item for that slot. If it's an upgrade, they just get the piece. If no one can show that, then *everyone* rolls (we call it a &quot;greed&quot; roll). The assumption is that everyone's &quot;need&quot; is equal. NBG folks will argue &quot;I have an alt...&quot;, but there's no way to proove that. You either proove you can and will use the item, or it's randomed by everyone. Most gear just ends up randomed, since with rare exceptions, most of the stuff that drops at a single group camp will *not* be an uprgrade for anyone at that camp. And in the rare case where it is, you just grats the person and let them get the gear (they clearly *do* need it, right?).<br><br>I've rarely ever seen this system abused in OoW zones. Gear drops are common enough, but still not quite &quot;uber&quot; enough, that they're generally just looked at as cash loot and split up via randoms. Most people are there for the exp rate, and for the rarer quest and item drops, so that other stuff is just gravy.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
