		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Wed, Mar 2nd 7:01 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=110832765395582215&num=73&page=1&post=1&replyto=110980830588184704"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=110980830588184704></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9795 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.03]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Heh. I mostly agree with czae as well. I make a distinction between cawu and nbg because most groups of people make a distinction between them as well. Technically nbg is *supposed* to be cawu based, but in most cases, it's not. Different people define &quot;need&quot; differently, even when they're not being dishonest. So the guy with a dozen+ alts scattered across 2 or 3 accounts &quot;needs&quot; gear for all of them and will often justify that as why he'll put his hat in for a nbg claim.<br><br>CAWU is pretty universally recognized to mean that the character you are playing, right now, and in this group can and will use the item. Not an alt. Not a friend. Not a guildmember. You. Yeah. Some folks will carry around junk gear to get shots at more stuff, but there are people who'll &quot;cheat&quot; at anything, and there isn't much you can do about them. They usually reap the rewards of their dishonesty eventually, so I'm not going to lose sleep over that.<br><br>When you add that system to a &quot;shared drops&quot; method, it's not a problem anyway. I've literally been in WoS or NC groups where every single person walks away with a rune, a &quot;greed&quot; item, maybe a charm item for sale (also greed item realy), and maybe a couple got a second rune. It's just not a problem that I've seen. If you really really want to fake a piece of gear in order to get one extra greed item, go for it. You're not really getting that much IMO.<br><br><br>Ldder. I've never been a fan of the &quot;trickle down&quot; upgrade system. I've seen it used in guilds (and we even used it a time or two on raids, but not in a long time). It *can* work with a group of friends, it's a horrible idea in a pickup group though. Even ignoring the obvious situation where someone gets the nbg award with his &quot;fake&quot; piece of junk armor, it's still rife with problems.<br><br>First off, it's unfair to the guy who just got the item. In many cases, the &quot;gain&quot; for getting a new piece of gear is that you return the old to the &quot;sell or alt&quot; pile. So if I spent 20k on a piece of armor, then a piece drops in a group (yeah, like that'll happen, but bear with me), that is a slight upgrade, I'd certainly like to have that upgrade. It *is* an upgrade. I should be allowed to roll/whatever for it. But now, I'm out the 20k I spent as well. If I'd not spent that money in the first place, and suffered with whatever piece of junk I'd had in that slot before, I would *still* have won that armor upgrade, but would have saved myself 20k.<br><br>That's problem number one. The other problem is no-drop gear. On the one hand, no-drop gear *sucks* from an upgrade perspective. It's often nice to offset the cost of an upgrade with the knowledge that you can sell the old piece of gear. But no-drop is totally going to screw up your system. If the slot I'm replacing is a no-drop item, I *can't* give that item back to the group. So what do we do? Not award it to me? It's kinda unfair for one guy to have to give up a piece of his existing gear to get an upgrade drop, but another guy doesn't. Admittedly, the other guy gains no use from that no-drop gear either, but that's not the point. From the group's perspective, it's inconsistent and unfair.<br><br><br>As a general rule, anything that is droppable is &quot;fair game&quot; for anyone in the group. You may choose to not roll for it if you think it should go to someone who can use it, or choose not to. That's your (and your groupmates) choice. As Czae points out, all droppable stuff has value to everyone. I could sell it, or tribute it, and gain just as much benfit from it as someone who'll wear it. I tend to be ok with folks claiming cawu, but that really only works in camps where semi-valuable items drop at pretty regular rates, so it's just not a problem. I kinda think of it as &quot;trading&quot; your drops. At least in the OoW zone camps, the &quot;junk&quot; items that drop are pretty similar in value, so you can mostly think of them as interchangable. If someone wants a particular piece as their drop, then by all means, let them have it. Obviously, that system does not work as well in a location with a wide difference in drop values, or locations where the entire group will only get one &quot;good&quot; item.<br><br>You always have to adjust to the camp you are at and just use common sense. If someone's arguing NBG for the one item that's dropped in the 3 hours you've been at a camp, you might want to question that. But if you're killing a named mob about 2-3 times an hour, and getting one or two drops per named, it's just not an issue.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
